{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_20","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > /tmp/research_31984.txt <<'EOF'\n# RESEARCH\n\nIssue: #31984\nDate: 2026-05-10\n\n## Sources consulted\n\n- ENZYME EC 1.2.5.3: accepted name \"'`aerobic carbon monoxide dehydrogenase`; reaction `CO + a quinone + H2O = a quinol + CO2`.\n  - https://enzyme.expasy.org/EC/1.2.5.3\n- Rhea 48880: mapped to EC 1.2.5.3 and GO:0008805.\n  - https://www.rhea-db.org/rhea/48880\n- ENZYME EC 1.2.7.4: accepted name `anaerobic carbon-monoxide dehydrogenase`; reaction `CO + 2 oxidized [2Fe-2S]-[ferredoxin] + H2O = 2 reduced [2Fe-2S]-[ferredoxin] + CO2 + 2 H(+)`.\n  - https://enzyme.expasy.org/EC/1.2.7.4\n- Rhea 21040: mapped to EC 1.2.7.4 and GO:0043885.\n  - https://www.rhea-db.org/rhea/21040\n\n## Conclusions relevant to the edit\n\n- GO:0008805 is currently outdated in both label semantics and reaction equation. Current EC and Rhea support a quinone acceptor, not cytochrome b-561.\n- Reparenting GO:0008805 under GO:0052738 is consistent with the EC 1.2.5.- acceptor class.\n- GO:0043885 already has the correct high-level classification under the iron-sulfur acceptor parent, but its definition should be updated to the more specific current Rhea/EC stoichiometry.\n\n## Reference validation\n\n- No new PMIDs were introduced for this issue.\n- Definitions remain backed by EC/Rhea identifiers already present on the terms.\nEOF\ncp /tmp/research_31984.txt RESEARCH.md'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
